    {
        "content": "<p>It's not obvious to me that the output of the grothendiek construction is small in general</p>",
        "id": 195083445,
        "sender_full_name": "Brian Pinsky",
        "timestamp": 1587657987
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I assume the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>∫</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\int</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.11112em;vertical-align:-0.30612em;\"></span><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"margin-right:0.19445em;position:relative;top:-0.0005599999999999772em;\">∫</span></span></span></span> used to represent this construction is some kind of end or coend?  I don't have great intuition for ends, but this seems like a nice example</p>",
        "id": 195084112,
        "sender_full_name": "Brian Pinsky",
        "timestamp": 1587658314
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't think it is an end or coend...just a coincidence of notation.</p>",
        "id": 195084375,
        "sender_full_name": "Jade Master",
        "timestamp": 1587658439
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I <em>think</em> I remember reading that it's not quite (but it does look kinda like an end)</p>",
        "id": 195084381,
        "sender_full_name": "Jules Hedges",
        "timestamp": 1587658442
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"281268\">Brian Pinsky</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229457-MIT-Categories.20Seminar/topic/April.2023.20-.20Joe.20Moeller's.20talk/near/195083445\" title=\"#narrow/stream/229457-MIT-Categories.20Seminar/topic/April.2023.20-.20Joe.20Moeller's.20talk/near/195083445\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>It's not obvious to me that the output of the grothendiek construction is small in general</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>You can use the fact that a locally small category with a small set of objects is small.<br>\nIf you have a functor C^op -&gt; Cat, where C is small and Cat is the category of small categories, then the Grothendieck construction is still locally small (can you see why?). It is also small, because its set of objects is a disjoint union of small sets indexed over a small set (the objects of C).</p>",
        "id": 195084673,
        "sender_full_name": "Paolo Perrone",
        "timestamp": 1587658563
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"281268\">Brian Pinsky</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229457-MIT-Categories.20Seminar/topic/April.2023.20-.20Joe.20Moeller's.20talk/near/195084112\" title=\"#narrow/stream/229457-MIT-Categories.20Seminar/topic/April.2023.20-.20Joe.20Moeller's.20talk/near/195084112\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I assume the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>∫</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\int</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.11112em;vertical-align:-0.30612em;\"></span><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"margin-right:0.19445em;position:relative;top:-0.0005599999999999772em;\">∫</span></span></span></span> used to represent this construction is some kind of end or coend?  I don't have great intuition for ends, but this seems like a nice example</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Both the Grothendieck construction and coends are written as integrals because they both look like an \"area under the curve\", but they are not an example of one another, as far as I've seen. Yeah, this is unfortunate.</p>",
        "id": 195084825,
        "sender_full_name": "Paolo Perrone",
        "timestamp": 1587658630
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>okay thanks</p>",
        "id": 195084883,
        "sender_full_name": "Brian Pinsky",
        "timestamp": 1587658661
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"281268\">Brian Pinsky</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229457-MIT-Categories.20Seminar/topic/April.2023.20-.20Joe.20Moeller's.20talk/near/195084112\" title=\"#narrow/stream/229457-MIT-Categories.20Seminar/topic/April.2023.20-.20Joe.20Moeller's.20talk/near/195084112\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I assume the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>∫</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\int</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.11112em;vertical-align:-0.30612em;\"></span><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"margin-right:0.19445em;position:relative;top:-0.0005599999999999772em;\">∫</span></span></span></span> used to represent this construction is some kind of end or coend?  I don't have great intuition for ends, but this seems like a nice example</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>In fact, the Grothendieck construction <em>is</em> a kind of coend using the coslice (or slice) construction. Given F:C--&gt;Cat, the Grothendieck category of F is equivalent to the coend <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mo>∫</mo><mrow><mi>c</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>C</mi></mrow></msup><mi>F</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>c</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>×</mo><mi>c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">.</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\int^{c: C}  F(c) \\times c/C.</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.3423509999999998em;vertical-align:-0.30612em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"margin-right:0.19445em;position:relative;top:-0.0005599999999999772em;\">∫</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.036231em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.2579000000000002em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault mtight\">c</span><span class=\"mrel mtight\">:</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">c</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">c</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mord\">.</span></span></span></span></p>",
        "id": 195087051,
        "sender_full_name": "David Spivak",
        "timestamp": 1587659661
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh wow, cool!</p>",
        "id": 195087921,
        "sender_full_name": "Paolo Perrone",
        "timestamp": 1587660067
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>DARPA... search+rescue is search+destroy in the opposite category?</p>",
        "id": 195090596,
        "sender_full_name": "Jules Hedges",
        "timestamp": 1587661248
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I usually join over youtube live not zoom (it works better on my TV).  Are these breakout rooms  going to be a common feature in afterwards?  I can connect over zoom instead.</p>",
        "id": 195091336,
        "sender_full_name": "Brian Pinsky",
        "timestamp": 1587661598
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The category of elements is described as a coend in The Coend Calculus <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1501.02503.pdf\" title=\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1501.02503.pdf\">https://arxiv.org/pdf/1501.02503.pdf</a>, 4.2.2. Then after some generalizations, in 7.3.4 they jump all the way to the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\infty</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span></span></span></span> case...<br>\nI haven't read the lax coend stuff, but I assume that for the Grothendieck construction you just need a slight weakening to pseudo-coends. Luckily it's still the same formula, and you can get the intuition from the category of elements.</p>",
        "id": 195091478,
        "sender_full_name": "Christian Williams",
        "timestamp": 1587661667
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"281268\">Brian Pinsky</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229457-MIT-Categories.20Seminar/topic/April.2023.20-.20Joe.20Moeller's.20talk/near/195091336\" title=\"#narrow/stream/229457-MIT-Categories.20Seminar/topic/April.2023.20-.20Joe.20Moeller's.20talk/near/195091336\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I usually join over youtube live not zoom (it works better on my TV).  Are these breakout rooms  going to be a common feature in afterwards?  I can connect over zoom instead.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>It depends - let's see how the testing goes :)</p>",
        "id": 195091561,
        "sender_full_name": "Paolo Perrone",
        "timestamp": 1587661697
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That's also nice because it's a case of nerve and realization -- you could call the Grothendieck construction the \"slice realization\". This means it has an adjoint, the \"slice nerve\", that turns a category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>D</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">D</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span></span></span></span> into an indexed category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mo>−</mo><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>D</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Cat}(C/-,D)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">C</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">a</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">t</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 195092399,
        "sender_full_name": "Christian Williams",
        "timestamp": 1587662133
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>what unfortunate constructions of morphisms. there's rescue without search, and search without destroy (miss is frequent irl).</p>",
        "id": 195095458,
        "sender_full_name": "eric brunner",
        "timestamp": 1587663625
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275901\">Jules Hedges</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229457-MIT-Categories.20Seminar/topic/April.2023.20-.20Joe.20Moeller's.20talk/near/195090596\" title=\"#narrow/stream/229457-MIT-Categories.20Seminar/topic/April.2023.20-.20Joe.20Moeller's.20talk/near/195090596\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>DARPA... search+rescue is search+destroy in the opposite category?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Unfortunately I found out later they snuck in an <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>o</mi><mi>p</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">^{op}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.664392em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.664392em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault mtight\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault mtight\">p</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> when I wasn't looking -__-</p>",
        "id": 195095883,
        "sender_full_name": "Joe Moeller",
        "timestamp": 1587663850
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But that's why I ended up quitting the project.</p>",
        "id": 195096048,
        "sender_full_name": "Joe Moeller",
        "timestamp": 1587663942
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Here are my slides: <a href=\"https://joemathjoe.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/mit_seminar_talk.pdf\" title=\"https://joemathjoe.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/mit_seminar_talk.pdf\">https://joemathjoe.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/mit_seminar_talk.pdf</a></p>",
        "id": 195096139,
        "sender_full_name": "Joe Moeller",
        "timestamp": 1587663976
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In the spirit of \"why don't they build the whole airplane out of the black box\" given the equivalence between fibrations and indexed categories, and given that indexed categories are easier to present (in terms of having fewer conditions), why don't we always just do that?</p>",
        "id": 195123929,
        "sender_full_name": "Gershom",
        "timestamp": 1587678704
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That is my preference, and I think that's what is done much of the time. Dependent function types I think are basically the same as indexed categories, right?</p>",
        "id": 195128276,
        "sender_full_name": "Joe Moeller",
        "timestamp": 1587681618
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But fibrations are sometimes the more natural thing to consider, eg graphs over sets.</p>",
        "id": 195128819,
        "sender_full_name": "Joe Moeller",
        "timestamp": 1587682052
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Another thing, you can compose fibrations in an obvious way, I don't think it's at all easy to see how you would compose indexed categories, or even when they're composable.</p>",
        "id": 195128911,
        "sender_full_name": "Joe Moeller",
        "timestamp": 1587682115
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Hi all! Here's the video. <a href=\"https://youtu.be/DDECeQaGwYs\" title=\"https://youtu.be/DDECeQaGwYs\">https://youtu.be/DDECeQaGwYs</a></p>\n<div class=\"youtube-video message_inline_image\"><a data-id=\"DDECeQaGwYs\" href=\"https://youtu.be/DDECeQaGwYs\" title=\"https://youtu.be/DDECeQaGwYs\"><img src=\"https://i.ytimg.com/vi/DDECeQaGwYs/default.jpg\"></a></div>",
        "id": 195128968,
        "sender_full_name": "Paolo Perrone",
        "timestamp": 1587682165
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276650\">Gershom</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229457-MIT-Categories.20Seminar/topic/April.2023.20-.20Joe.20Moeller's.20talk/near/195123929\" title=\"#narrow/stream/229457-MIT-Categories.20Seminar/topic/April.2023.20-.20Joe.20Moeller's.20talk/near/195123929\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>In the spirit of \"why don't they build the whole airplane out of the black box\" given the equivalence between fibrations and indexed categories, and given that indexed categories are easier to present (in terms of having fewer conditions), why don't we always just do that?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This is a fun question, so it's good to think about a decategorified version of this function.  Given the equivalence between isomorphism classes of monos into <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> and characteristic functions <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>χ</mi><mspace></mspace><mspace width=\"0.1111111111111111em\"></mspace><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0.17em\"></mo><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">:</mo><mspace width=\"0.3333333333333333em\"></mspace><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\chi \\colon X \\to 2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8777699999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">χ</span><span class=\"mspace nobreak\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1111111111111111em;\"></span><span class=\"mpunct\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:-0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mrel\">:</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.3333333333333333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span></span></span></span>, and given that characteristic functions are easier to present (in terms of having fewer conditions), why don't we always just do that?</p>\n<p>Of course in material set theory we describe an isomorphism class of monos into <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> as a \"subset\" of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>, which simplifies things, but even without this trick I think both approaches would be useful.</p>",
        "id": 195135598,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1587688113
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276650\">Gershom</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229457-MIT-Categories.20Seminar/topic/April.2023.20-.20Joe.20Moeller's.20talk/near/195123929\" title=\"#narrow/stream/229457-MIT-Categories.20Seminar/topic/April.2023.20-.20Joe.20Moeller's.20talk/near/195123929\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>In the spirit of \"why don't they build the whole airplane out of the black box\" given the equivalence between fibrations and indexed categories, and given that indexed categories are easier to present (in terms of having fewer conditions), why don't we always just do that?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I agree, I find them easier to present that way, but anyone who wants to opine about these things had better be aware of B&eacute;nabou's notorious <a href=\"https://artscimedia.case.edu/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/14182624/Benabou-Fibered.pdf\" title=\"https://artscimedia.case.edu/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/14182624/Benabou-Fibered.pdf\">essay</a> on the subject. He does make some interesting points. For example, it's easy to prove that a composite of fibrations is a fibration. He says: now try proving <em>that</em> using indexed categories! He also has some worthwhile remarks on the notion of definability.</p>",
        "id": 195136025,
        "sender_full_name": "Todd Trimble",
        "timestamp": 1587688596
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>As John said, I don't think it should be regarded as a choice to make between the two, but rather that the flexibility of having two presentations of the same thing is a useful tool.  In between monos and fibrations we have the notion of an I-indexed family of sets that can be described as a function <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>I</mi><mo>→</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">I\\to \\mathrm{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">t</span></span></span></span></span> or as a function <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>I</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X\\to I</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span></span></span></span>, and both versions are useful.</p>",
